<subSubSection id="E0B775DB3C60FE3C18E8F868FB38FF60" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="26" pageId="9" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A81226503C60FE3C18E8F868FB38FF60" blockId="9.[151,1436,1608,2008]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1435,152,364]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="26" pageId="9" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="9AD9FA423C60FE3F18E8F868FECEF805" bold="true" box="[198,341,1944,1970]" pageId="9" pageNumber="25">Comments.</emphasis>
Nymphs of 
<taxonomicName id="6FAD5DD33C60FE3F19C6F869FDE1F805" authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[488,634,1945,1970]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longetron">
<emphasis id="9AD9FA423C60FE3F19C6F869FDE1F805" box="[488,634,1945,1970]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="25">A. longetron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are present almost exclusively in banks with marginal vegetation in areas with slow to moderate current; they resemble 
<taxonomicName id="6FAD5DD33C60FE3F1AC1F84FFCC6F86F" authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[751,861,1983,2008]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alphus">
<emphasis id="9AD9FA423C60FE3F1AC1F84FFCC6F86F" box="[751,861,1983,2008]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="25">A. alphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in several aspects, as mouthpart morphology and somewhat similar habitat (
<figureCitation id="30963AD53C63FE3C19E0FF68FDBCFF05" box="[462,551,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–30" captionStartId="10.[151,269,1396,1420]" captionTargetBox="[176,1411,433,1370]" captionTargetId="figure-252@10.[170,1417,421,1375]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 27–30. General aspect of Americabaetis nymphs’ habitat. 27. A. mecistognathus, sp. nov.; 28. A. alphus and A. longetron; 29. A. labiosus; 30. A. titthion." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302619/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="26">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). However, the distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="6FAD5DD33C63FE3C1BA1FF68FBBAFF06" authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[911,1057,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longetron">
<emphasis id="9AD9FA423C63FE3C1BA1FF68FBBAFF06" box="[911,1057,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="26">A. longetron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is far restricted when compared to that of 
<taxonomicName id="6FAD5DD33C63FE3C1926FF4DFEEDFF61" authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[264,374,189,214]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alphus">
<emphasis id="9AD9FA423C63FE3C1926FF4DFEEDFF61" box="[264,374,189,214]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="26">A. alphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The altitudinal range of this species varies from 
<quantity id="6F558BB53C63FE3C1B95FF4DFBF7FF60" box="[955,1132,189,215]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.17" metricValueMax="10.629999999999999" metricValueMin="3.71" pageId="10" pageNumber="26" unit="m" value="717.0" valueMax="1063.0" valueMin="371.0">371 to 1063 m</quantity>
.a.s.l.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
